text=:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts%0a:Title: Tone Systems Comparing English and Southern Min%0a:Author: JoshuaC%0a:Section: F%0a:Completed: 19.02.2021 - 20:10%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-215319-652990#%0a* [-05.05.2021 - 14:53-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-215319-652990#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aEnglish has no tones, while Min (Southern) has a complex tone system%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aTone involves using differences in pitch in order to distinguish between the meaning or grammar of individual words. Tones can describe a relatively flat pitch on words, or a moving pattern such as the pitch rising from low to high or falling from high to low. Tones with moving patterns of pitch are called contour tones. %0aThis is somewhat similar to intonation, which also involves changes in pitch. However, the difference between tone and intonation is that intonation uses the changes in pitch for more general functions such as emphasizing certain parts of a sentence or identifying sentences as a question, rather than changing the meaning of words.%0aThe category of tone system differentiates between languages with and without tones and describes how many different tones a language has. The World Atlas of Linguistic Structures Online (WALS) has three values for tone systems – no tones, simple tone system, and complex tone system. No tones describes languages with no tones, a simple tone system describes languages with only 2 different tones, while a complex tone system is used to describe languages with more than 2 tones. %0aEnglish is categorized as having no tones, while Min (Southern) is described to have a complex tone system. English does have intonation. For example, there is a rising tone at the end of certain yes/no questions. However, changes in pitch do not change the meaning of syllables or words. Therefore, English is not considered to have any tones.%0aMin (Southern) includes a range of languages, with distinct differences in the language spoken by different groups in regions such as China, Taiwan, and Malaysia. While these languages all have a complex tone system, there is a difference in the number of distinct tones within each language. For example, Hokkien is generally regarded as having 8 different tones. However, Hokkien from certain regions such as Taiwan or Penang are regarded as having 6 or 7 tones as they do not distinguish between certain tones. The tone pattern may also change between variations of Hokkien. %0aOne question I have is the process of learning and recognizing distinct tones in languages. I learned Mandarin Chinese as part of my formal school system, and have no issues recognizing the four basic tones in the language. On the other hand, I have very limited proficiency in Hokkien, having only learned it from hearing my immediate family members communicate. While I largely understand sentences in Hokkien, I cannot really speak the language outside of common phrases or sentences. However, I am unable to identify the different tones within the Hokkien language and tend to link the pronunciation of Hokkien words back to the 4 tones of Mandarin Chinese I am familiar with. Therefore, I wonder if this inability to recognize tones can be attributed to my lack of proficiency in the language, existing familiarity with another language with a different tonal system, or lack of formal schooling and study of the language.%0a%0aReferences:%0aMaddieson, Ian. “Tone.” The World Atlas of Language Structures Online, Leipzig: Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology., wals.info/chapter/13. %0a“Taiwanese Hokkien.” Wikipedia, Wikimedia Foundation, 11 Feb. 2021, en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taiwanese_Hokkien. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
