orized as having no tones, while Min (Southern) is described to have a complex tone system. English does have intonation. For example, there is a rising tone at the end of certain yes/no questions. However, changes in pitch do not change the meaning of syllables or words. Therefore, English is not considered to have any tones.%0a%3c Min (Southern) includes a range of languages, with distinct differences in the language spoken by different groups in regions such as China, Taiwan, and Malaysia. While these languages all have a complex tone system, there is a difference in the number of distinct tones within each language. For example, Hokkien is generally regarded as having 8 different tones. However, Hokkien from certain regions such as Taiwan or Penang are regarded as having 6 or 7 tones as they do not distinguish between certain tones. The tone pattern may also change between variations of Hokkien. %0a%3c One question I have is the process of learning and recognizing distinct tones in languages. I learned Mandarin Chinese as part of my formal school system, and have no issues recognizing the four basic tones in the language. On the other hand, I have very limited proficiency in Hokkien, having only learned it from hearing my immediate family members communicate. While I largely understand sentences in Hokkien, I cannot really speak the language outside of common phrases or sentences. However, I am unable to identify the different tones within the Hokkien language and tend to link the pronunciation of Hokkien words back to the 4 tones of Mandarin Chinese I am familiar with. Therefore, I wonder if this inability to recognize tones can be attributed to my lack of proficiency in the language, existing familiarity with another language with a different tonal system, or lack of formal schooling and study of the language.%0a%3c %0a%3c References:%0a%3c Maddieson, Ian. “Tone.” The World Atlas of Language Structures Online, Leipzig: Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology., wals.info/chapter/13. %0a%3c “Taiwanese Hokkien.” Wikipedia, Wikimedia Foundation, 11 Feb. 2021, en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taiwanese_Hokkien. %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
